{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515868"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:35:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:35:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12516"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12516"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.64,0.04,0.04,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5017"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33472"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5017"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12516"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18872"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3542"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8190"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8310"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8349"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42771"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/33472"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents with a one week history of neck pain and difficulty in swallowing. She is normally in good health, but did have an upper respiratory tract infection a few weeks back. On examination her blood pressure is 135/85 mmHg, pulse 110/min and temperature 38.3\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. There is tenderness and swelling of the thyroid gland, which is firm to touch. There are no signs of ophthalmopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations show an elevated erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) and C-reactive protein (CRP) elevated serum free T4 levels and decreased serum TSH level. Thyroid peroxidase (TPO) and thyroglobulin antibodies are negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Subacute lymphocytic thyroiditis","De Quervain\u0027s thyroiditis","Hashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis","Graves\u0027 disease","Riedel thyroiditis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s presentation of neck pain as well as the physical examination findings are consistent with\u003Cstrong\u003E De Quervain\u0027s thyroiditis,\u003C/strong\u003E a\u003Cem\u003Eka\u003C/em\u003E subacute granulomatous thyroiditis. The elevated serum free T4 levels and decreased serum TSH level suggest hyperthyroidism as is characteristic in the first 4-8 weeks of De Quervain\u0027s thyroiditis followed by a state of hypothyroidism which usually returns back to euthyroid state in 4-6 months. Hyperthyroidism is due to release of stored T4 due to the inflammation of the gland. Hence classically this condition is associated with elevated FT4 and low uptake in a radioactive thyroid scan as compared to Graves\u0027 disease which is associated with elevated FT4 and increased uptake in a thyroid scan. In subacute thyroiditis the gland itself is under functioning, hence the subsequent phase of hypothyroidism. This is a transient self-limiting inflammation of the thyroid gland, which can be caused by radiation, trauma or infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubacute lymphocytic thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E is another type of subacute thyroiditis, but it presents as a painless swelling, rather than the tender and firm thyroid gland in this case. It also presents initially as hyperthyroidism proceeded by hypo and eventually euthyroid state, but it is associated with elevated thyroglobulin antibodies as it is usually autoimmune in nature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic autoimmune disorder that typically presents with a painless goiter and is associated with elevated thyroid antibodies. It usually presents with hypothyroidism with bouts of hyperthyroidism initially. The acute presentation of the patient with fever and negative antibodies makes Hashimoto\u0027s least likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGraves\u0027 disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a type of autoimmune hyperthyroidism that typically presents with a diffusely enlarged thyroid gland, along with symptoms of hyperthyroidism, ophthalmopathy and dermopathy being the characteristic features absent in this case. Fever, thyroid tenderness and absence of antibodies direct the diagnosis more towards De Quervain\u0027s thyroiditis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERiedel thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare form of chronic thyroiditis characterised by fibrosis of the thyroid gland, resulting in a hard and fixed thyroid mass with symptoms of compression, hypoparathyroidism or hypothyroidism. The acute presentation, symptoms of hyperthyroidism and the tender and firm thyroid gland rather than hard and fixed makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["De Quervain\u0027s thyroiditis (subacute thyroiditis) is a self-limiting condition associated with a triphasic clinical course of hyperthyroidism, hypothyroidism, and return to normal thyroid function."],"references":["Tabassom A, Edens MA. De Quervain Thyroiditis. 2018 Jan.","Fariduddin MM, Singh G. Thyroiditis. [Updated 2022 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18872"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12516"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/18872"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-03-09T08:39:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-03-09T08:39:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5017"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33472"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"